## built a list of decreasing runs

As the list is scanned, if the current element is &lt;= the element at the end of the last run, add it to the run.  It not, start a new run with the current element.

The example array becomes `[[10, 2], [4], [14, 1], [7]]`.

It is then a simple matter of scanning each run and doing something with the elements that are larger than element[i].

Here is example code that processes the input array, and returns a list of lists.

    def bigger_so_far(seq):
        results = []
        runs = []
    
        for element in seq:
            if runs:
                if element &gt; runs[-1][-1]:
                    runs.append([])
                runs[-1].append(element)
    
            else:
                runs.append([element])
    
            result = []
            for run in runs:
                for j in run:
                    if j &lt;= element:
                        break
                    result.append(j)
    
            results.append(result)
            
        print(runs)
            
        return results

